724081f-b.text:
Washington Street (thru the center, from fore to background) south from Rector Street (foreground, not seen) to Battery Park. beyond the latter is the Upper Bay and Governor's Island. At the right is the new Downtown Athletic Club over-towering the partially constructed United Fruit Bldg. To the left on Greenwich Street are the rears of the Cunard, the Bowling Green and the Washington Buildings. The low roofed rookeries between these thoroughfares are occupied mainly by Syrians and Greeks and for one of Manhattans national sectors.
July 30, 1930.
Views 1 and 2
P.L. Spnerr

724079f-a.text:
Washington Street, east side, north from (No. 101, axtreme right), Rector Street, showing an early view of this downtown area which has undergone many changes. The most radical was the replacement of the double, white front tenement (No. 105-107) by the Bowling Green Neighborhood House. The tenement adjacent to same became St. Georges Roman Catholic Church about the same time (about 19277). For views of both structures mentioned see files under their respective addresses.
April 1911.
Geo. L. Balgue.
